The Revival of the Great Leader
London —— It has been two centuries since the Battle of Waterloo, Napoleon's catastrophic defeat in which severely damaged France's self-esteem to such an extent that General de Gaulle omitted any mention of the battle when writing France's military history.
Despite this, if you acknowledge "greatness" as a personal quality, both Napoleon and de Gaulle could be considered the greatest leaders in history.
Marx and Tolstoy would say that there is fundamentally no such thing as a "great leader."
In Marx's view, the class struggle in France created the environment in which "grotesque mediocrities" like Napoleon could become heroes.
In Tolstoy's view, Napoleon was not an especially outstanding general, and his victories should be attributed to the courage and devotion of the French soldiers who fought at Borodino.
Whether or not Napoleon was great, we must determine whether "greatness" can be used to describe any leader.
If the answer is affirmative, then who can be described as great?
Political philosopher Isaiah Berlin believed that a great leader must meet two particularly important criteria.
First, can this leader recognize historical trends?
Otto von Bismarck did, as did his German compatriot Konrad Adenauer; borrowing Bismarck's unforgettable phrase, both heard "the rustling of the cloak of God."
Second, did this leader make important decisions?
Of course, if a leader is forced to make decisions, he or she should neither be blamed for them nor take credit for them.
Therefore, the key is whether the leader had the opportunity to weigh pros and cons and make the right decisions on behalf of the nation.
De Gaulle should therefore be listed on any ranking of great leaders.
He almost single-handedly led France out of the post-World War II decline.
After regaining power in 1958, he once again saved his country by suppressing two failed coups, ending the Algerian War, and drafting the constitution of the Fifth Republic.
Like British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, de Gaulle gave the French a new worldview and established their position in the postwar global order.
In fact, the ultimate impact of de Gaulle and Churchill in establishing their countries' worldviews was somewhat too great.
Their successors viewed the world—and the role of their own countries—in ways that constrained rational inquiry and distorted decision-making for years to come.
The result was that leaders of both countries afterwards failed to achieve accomplishments that could rival those of the two great leaders.
But there is another British prime minister who can be compared to them: she is Margaret Thatcher, a very controversial figure, liked by as many people as she is disliked.
Even her resignation 25 years ago stemmed from resistance within her own cabinet and party.
But it is not necessary to be loved by everyone to be a great leader.
In fact, even Thatcher's critics cannot deny her influence.
In addition to being the first female prime minister of the United Kingdom and among the earliest female prime ministers in other countries, Thatcher helped turn around Britain's economic decline.
Moreover, her attacks on overly powerful unions enhanced the country's manageability at a time when it seemed to be sliding into turmoil and chaos.
Given this, she undoubtedly has the right to be considered a candidate for "great leader."
Similarly, although far from flawless, Deng Xiaoping of China is also qualified to be considered a great leader.
In addition to assisting Mao in wrongdoing, Deng also played a decisive role in ordering the 1989 Tiananmen Square massacre.
But Deng also revitalized the market, leading China on an unprecedented path of development and prosperity that ultimately lifted hundreds of millions of Chinese people out of poverty.
Many people consider Lee Kuan Yew, the founder of Singapore and its long-serving prime minister, to be extremely great, although he may have wished to showcase his talents on a larger stage.
In fact, the size of a country does not seem to affect a person's ability to become a great leader.
I certainly meant no offense when I said that a small country like Luxembourg is unlikely to produce a great leader, especially as the country's political atmosphere is generally not very contentious.
The vast territory of the United States is ample enough to be a cradle for great leaders.
Some presidents have indeed achieved considerable accomplishments.
Harry Truman and Dwight Eisenhower — though not intellectual giants — demonstrated remarkable judgment in establishing the postwar international order that supported world peace for decades.
Others, including Ronald Reagan and Bill Clinton, possessed extraordinary talents — the ability to inspire and the art of persuasion.
John F. Kennedy combined both strengths.
He accomplished a great task: defusing the Cuban Missile Crisis.
His gift for inspiration was unparalleled; in fact, his assassination after his death solidified the tradition he left behind.
In South Africa, no one has yet emerged as a great figure since the death of President Mandela, who combined courage, authority, and the graceful magnanimity of a great leader.
In fact, he was the most charming and captivating leader I have ever encountered; the other two — former UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan and former U.S. Secretary of State Colin Powell — were either Africans or African Americans.
So what about today?
The only one qualified to claim greatness is the de facto leader of the EU, German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Like former Chancellor Helmut Kohl, she was often underestimated at first but rarely made mistakes when making important decisions.
Kohl crafted generous terms for German reunification; Merkel stood against Putin during his invasion of Ukraine and adopted a tolerant approach toward the immigration crisis.
I think Marx and Tolstoy are wrong.
Political leaders — those who exercise political power — can change the situation, for better or worse.
Merkel is today's most obvious example of a leader who has charted a course for Europe to navigate a difficult survival crisis.
